{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580357/1949030301/0382.xml":{"full_text":"Thursday, March 8, 1949\nTories Use Slow\nStarvation On\nLabor Department\nBy BRADFORD V. CARTER\nThere\u2019s more ways\nkilling a government\nerrs by siding with\nmen and women of\nnnd commits the sin\nserve their interests. Tory Con\ngressmen in recent years have\nfound that there\u2019s a special treat\nment for such agencies.\nthan one of\nagency that\nthe working\nthe country,\nof trying to\ni\nQuietly but thoroughly, they\u2019ve\nproceeded to kill such agencies by\ncutting down on their funds. They\ndid it with the Farm Security ad\nministration, which tried to protect\nthe interests of migrant workers\nand small farmers, and scores of\nothers.\nThe most .spectacular example,\nthough, is what has happened to\nthe Labor Department. For the\nyear that ended in mid-1947, the\nDepartment got $32 million from\nCongress. In 1948, that was cut to\n$22 million, and some bureaus were\nslashed as much as 55% by the\n80th Congress. In the current year,\nthe 80th Congress not only made\ncuts, but took awSy from the De\npartment entirely two of its most\nimportant functions\u2014those \"carried\non by the Federal Mediation\nConciliation Service, and the US\nEmployment Service. Total voted\nin 1948 was $15 million.\nNow, however, unionists might\nassume that things would be better\nfor the Labor Department.\nQuite the reverse is true. Even\nthe Budget Bureau recommenda\ntions which President Truman sent\nup to Congress would only pro\nvide $1 million more than the 80th\nCongress grudgingly voted last\nyear. And that increase is account\ned for in the funds proposed for\nBureau of Labor Statistics. Other\ndivisions would continue at their\npresent starvation level. The\nWomen\u2019s Bureau, never overly big,\nhad all of its field offices abolished\nby the 80th Congress. This year,\neven though it would only cost a\ntotal of $60,000 to $70,000 for some\nvery useful services for women\nworkers, the field offices are still\nshut tight Under the Budget Bur\neau proposal.\nThe Division of Labor Standards\nstill won\u2019t be able to resume its\nlabor education services, just start\ned after the war, and nipped by\nthe 80th Congress. It will have\nonly a very limited safety educa\ntion program, reaching only the\ntop levels of management and\nworkers, rather than providing im\naginative, striking material to\nbring information on safety stand\nards and safety education right\ninto every shop and mill in the\nBE SURE\nOF ALL THE\nthings you want\nThat new refrigerator, the sleek\nmodern car, new furniture for\nthe living room, the trip to places\nyou\u2019ve always wanted to see\u2014\nthey can be yours with regular\nsavings. Save now for the time\nwhen your dollars will buy a lot\nmore of the things you\u2019ve want\ned. The time to start is next\npayday. Why not visit us then\nand walk out with one of our\nsavings account books and the\ncertantiy of future happiness in\nyour pocket!\nSAVE now at\nFirst National\nMember FDIC\nEast Liverpool\u2019s Oldest Bank\nPhone 914\nfor happier\nSPENDING later\nT-H CAUSED FRICTION\u2014\nChairman Paul M. Herzog of the\nNLRB last week sent a letter to\nSen. Wayne Morse (R., Ore.) stat\ning that the Taft-Hartley act has\ncaused friction between the board\nand its general counsel, Robert N.\nDenham. Morse said the counsel\nshould be made subordinate to the\nboard in the new labor bill.\nLabor Extension\nBill Approved By\nSenate Committee\nWashington (LPA)\u2014The bill to\nset up a Labor Extension Service in\nthe Labor Department was report\ned favorably by the Senate Labor\nCommittee last week, the day after\nconclusion of the hearings on Taft\nHartley repeal.\nS. 110, authored by Chairman El\nbert Thomas (D, Utah), would\nauthorize provision of services thru\nstate educational institutions to\nwage earners. Classes and otner re\nsources would be made available to\nunions, under a program supervis\ned by a state advisory board.\nThe measure is expected to pass\nthe Senate, and then it will be up\nto the House Labor Committee,\nwhich has before it a bill identical\nwith the Senate one, written by\nRep. Thor C. Tollefson (R, Wash.).\nThere would be fewer strikes\n\u201cwhen people sitting on opposite\nsides of the tabla are equally well\nequipped and well-informed,\u201d Tol\nlefson said in a radio forum broad\ncast for west coast audiences last\nweek. He advocated quick passage\nof his Labor Extension Service bill\nas one step in this direction.\nOn the same discussion, AFL\nLegislative Representative Walter\nMason told listeners that \u201cone of\nthe strongest arguments for the\npassage of this act is the great op\nportunity I can see to give workers\nthe vision of, and the equipment\nfor, cooperation with management.\u201d\nEvery section of the labor move\nment supports and endorses the\nbill, Chairman Hilda Smith of the\nNat\u2019l Committee for Extension of\nLabor Education pointed out in\nsumming up the discussion.\ncountry.\nThe next steps oh the budget\nproposals are now being taken. In\naccordance with Congress\u2019 proce\ndure, the House Appropriations\nCommittee has set up a subcom\nmittee which is now holding ex\ntensive hearings at which Labor\nDep\u2019t officials \u201cjustify\u201d the funds,\nand spokesmen of interested or\nganizations can also appear in\nclosed sessions. The secrecy is\njustified by Congressmen on the\ngrounds that public hearings would\ncomplicate their delicate work. The\ntranscript of the hearings is made\npublic when the subcommittee re\nports and the full committee pre\nsents the report to the Housen\nMembers of the subcommittee\nnow working over the Labor De\npartment fund bill are: Chairman\nJohn E. Fogarty (D., R. I.), and\nDemocrats E. H. Hedrick (W. Va.),\nC. C. McGrath (N. Y.), and Re\npublicans Frank B. Keefe (Wis.)\nand Errett P. Scrivener (Kans.).\nDeadline for action is June 30th.\nBetween now and then, there will\nhave to be a lot of quiet *but ef\nfective lobbying if the Labor De\npartment is to be rescued from its\npresent pitiful state.\nFurniture-- Stoves\nBedding\u2014Curtains\nDrapery\u2014Rugs--Carpets\nPaint- Appliances\nDinner Cooking Ware\nSeven Floors Of Quality Furniture And All Furnish*\nings To Make A House A Comfortable Home*\nEstablished 1880 East Liverpool, Ohio\nConvenient Terms\nCROOK\u2019S\n\u201cTHE BEST PLACE TO BUY AFTER ALL\"\nThese are the days in which econ\nomists and pretenders to the title\nare making forecasts and guesses\nas to what\u2019s ahead\u2014\u201clevelling-off\u201d,\nrecession, depression? You can\nname it and you can have it.\nSo here\u2019s the fling of this column\nabout the domestic future.\nDepression is not in the cards in\nthe foreseeable future.\nNobody knows exactly what is\nmeant by the tkrm \u201crecession\u201d, so\nit had better be abandoned. Equal\nly, nobody knows exactly what is\nmeant by the term \u201clevelling-off\u201d,\nso that can go into the discard also.\nRecession should mean to go\nbackward\u2014but to what point? Tq\nlevel off would normally mean to\ncoast on the present grade. That\ncould be done if the economic world\nwere a static world\u2014one without\nmovement. But it isn\u2019t and by its\nnature it cannot be one.\nWhere does that leave us? Well,\nit ought to mean having a look\nwithout getting bound up to a set\ngroup of words. Let\u2019s try it.\nWe are not going to have-a de\npression for several reasons. One\nreason is that the Marshall Plan\nwill do a lot to prevent a depres\nsion. Another reason is the fact\nthat the government now has vast\npowers to do things which can\nstimulate, modify or retard the\nmovement of our economy and in\nalmost any given section or dir\nection.\nWe might as well add to those\nfacts the further fact that war\nsavings bonds are selling in larger\namounts and that such institutions\nas building and loan associations\nare prospering, with plenty of\nmonby going in as savings.\nNew industries, resulting from\ninvention and discovery in the\nworld of chemistry will continue\nto absorb workers\u2014and money.\nThe atomic energy program alone\nis of such hugh proportions that it\nwill be a mighty factor in our na\ntional economy. And it isn\u2019t alone,\nby any means.\nNow what is happening is im\nportant and not too complicated.\nIn many fields manufacture is\ncatching up to demand. The per\nfectly natural result is that buyers\nare more careful. They shop\naround. They look for quality and\nthey look for price. The run-away\nsellers\u2019 market is gone in many\nmajor lines.\nBut that isn\u2019t depression. Nor is\nit even what some call recession.\nCommon sense among buyers is\ngetting a chance to get to work\nand that\u2019s what it is doing.\nTwo years ago people who need\ned furniture had to buy whatever\njunk was available. Today they can\nlook around and they do look\naround. Further, people with a\nlittle money to spend have got over\nthe idea that they must spend this\nweek all that they earned\nweek. So, they buy carefully\nthey save some, too.\nFACTS YOU MUST KNOW\n(Prepared by The Public and Labor Relations Bureau, N. Y. City)\nThe butter lobby, aware of public sentiment for removal of\nobstacles to the manufacture and sale of margarine, has offered a com\npromise. It is willing to have margarine taxes and license fees repeal\ned, if only the federal ban on the colored product is allowed to stand.\nThe phony character of this compromise plan is transparent. If the\nbutter lobby has its way, all gains scored in the fight against anti\nmargarine state legislation will be lost.\n\nWhat are the facts? Over the years, the daiiy industry has agitat\ned for additional laws to restrict margarine. These restrictions, includ\ning the principal one of a 10-cent per pound federal tax on yellow\nmargarine, remain in force\u2014despite the fact that federal and state pure\nfood laws guarantee the high standard and proper labeling of mar\ngarine.\nButter, on the other hand, is exempt from these requirements.\nArtificial color may be and is added to butter without stating this fact\non the label. Privileged dairy interests were able to prevent butter\nfrom having to be labeled as margarine must be labeled.,\nHousewives could obviously trim their food budget if they were\npermitted to buy margarine tax-free like every other food. Margarine\nshould be colored yellow during the process of manufacture, just as\npractically all creamery butter is artificially colored\u2014without penalty,\nrestriction or any statement on the package.\nThe butter lobby is trying to becloud the repeal issue with its so\ncalled compromise. If you favor the lifting of margarine restrictions\nwithout ifs and buts, tell your Congressman and Senator so. If you\nsupport labor\u2019s demand that the people should be able to buy margarine\nready colored, without paying a \u201cspite\u201d tax of ten cents per pound, in\nsist on a repeal bill providing for free manufacture and sale of yellow\nmargarine. Nothing else will do.\nERRY\nTREE\nlast\nand\nde-\nThat\u2019s healthy. That\u2019s not\npression, or fear of depression. It\nis, in a way, a sign of confidence\nthat the future is going to be\nworth saving for.\nOf course some lines are going\nto have a bit of hard sledding. I\nknow a city in which far too many\nsmall store buildings have been\nbuilt.\nPeople with a few dollars, who\ndon\u2019t know about the change in\nbuying pace, have been induced to\nopen small establishments. Some\nof them will fail and some of the\nrents will have to come down.\nOur economy, again, is not static.\nIt doesn\u2019t ride an even tide and it\nnever will, unless it becomes a\nstate controlled economy\u2014and then\nmatters will be immediately much\nworse.\nBut while the Marshall Plan\nworks and if President Truman\u2019s\nplan is added, there is no more\ndanger of depression than there is\ni THE POTTERS HERALD, EAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO\nComment On\nWorld Events\nThe European recovery program\nis brought home to every person\nin the United States by figures of\nthe National Industrial Conference\nBoard, indicating that the program\nis costing the American public\nabout $31 a person, or \u201croughly,\n$113 for an average American\nfamily.\u201d\nAmerican aid umfer tire program\naverages about $17 a person, mean\ning that aid ranges from $2 to $74\nper capita in various countries, the\nboard found. Greece is the largest\nbeneficiary to date, the report said\nher aid amounting to about 15 per\ncent of its national income at 1947\nprices.\nThe report did not take into ac\ncount the program\u2019s \u201cinfluence on\nparticular areas, prices or other\naspects- of our economic system\u201d\nand it admitted that its data is far\nfrom complete. \u201cThe calculations\nmay only be regarded as illustra\ntive of the magnitudes involved,\u201d\nit said, \u201cratjier than anything like\nabsolute figures.\u201d\nWith the program reaching into\nevery pocketbook in the United\nStates, it is of vital interest to\nevery American that the program\nbe administered as economically,\nbut at the same time as effectively,\nas is possible under existing cir\ncumstances. Providing the public\nwith full information on the pro\ngram will serve this objective.\nChina should receive no Ameri\ncan aid whatsoever if Communists\nare permitted to enter the govern\nment of that strife-torn nation, the\nFree Trade Union Committee, AFL,\ndeclared in a vigorous and tifnely\nstatement. The committee, headed\nby Matthew Woll, AFL vice pres\nident, urged President Truman and\nCongress to call a conference of all\ndemocratic nations \u201cto work out a\ncommon program of action to stem\nthe tide of Communist tyranny and\nto bolster the truly democratic\nforces of Asia.\u201d\nThe Free Trade Union Commit\ntee warned that American aid to a\ncoalition government that included\nCommunists would be disasterous.\n\u201cThe Communists in China, like the\nCommunists elsewhere,\u201d thd com\nmittee warned, \u201care nothing but\ntools and spies of the Soviets.\u201d\nAFL views on China and the\nUnited States are further set forth\nin an American Federationist edit\norial by William Green, which\nstrongly emphasizes aid to enable\nChina to improve its industry and\nagriculture.\nDeclaring the fall of China to\nthe Communists would be a \u201cworld\nwide calamity,\u201d the Federationist\nsays that \u201ca dark cloud obscures\nthe future!\u2019 of that nation and con\ntinues\n\u201cOur program of economic aid to\nChina, though limited, was design\ned to begin industrial and rural re\nconstruction with engineering as\nsistance in reconstructing and\nequipping industries and agricul\ntural experts to demonstrate scien\ntific methods to improve seeds,\ncattle, poultry and first practices\nin soil cultivation. Chinese educa\ntors were working with our ex\nperts.\n\u201cWe hope the tide of Communist\nconquest can be localized. China is\nthe most densely populated coun\ntry in the world where, as one re\nporter says, \u2018Nothing is easy, but\nnearly everything is possible.\u2019 With\nconstructive assistance China may\nyet adjust its farming to scientific\npractices and thus improve food\nand living for all, adapting its in\ndustries to modern methods.\u201d\nWINS KEY BYELECTION\nLondon (LPA)\u2014Setting a record\nfor a party in power, the Labor\nParty last week won its 31st Com\nmons victory in a vital West Lon\ndon byelection, regarded my many\nas a straw vote for the next na\ntional election.\nof the moon slapping us in the face.\nBut economists must prognos\nticate and some of them must be\ngloomy. Let them have their merry\ntime, but don\u2019t let them kid you.\nFOR PRESIDENT\n(Vote for Ona)\nDUFFY, JAMES M. (Tumor)\nLocal Union No. 78 Buffalo, N. Y.\nFINLAY. LARRY (Rggoanam)\nLocal Union No. 12--------------- East Liverpool Ohio\nJOHNSTON, HARRY 8. (Docorating Dbusan)\nLocal Union No. 124 ...........East Liverpool Ohio\nWHIPPIER. NORMAN (Linar)\nLocal Union No. 124 East Liverpool Ohio\nFOR SECRETARY-TREASURER\n(Vota for Ono)\nCALHOON, P. K. (Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 9 East LivorpooL Ohio\nJONES. ED. J. (Castor)\nLocal Union No. 44 Sabring. Ohio\nJORDAN, CHAS. F.\nLocal Union No. 59 Sobring. Ohio\nPAKER. LAWRENCE F. (Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 113 _______.Loa Angolo* CalH.\nBALSBERRY, GEORGE M. (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 24 WoIbviHo, Ohio\nSHUMAN, LEWIS (Tumor)\nLocal Union No. 10 East UvorpooL Ohio\nFOR FIRST VICE PRESIDENT\n(Vote lor Ono)\nCURRY, ED. (Docorating Kihunan)\nLocal Union No. 124 East LivorpooL Ohio\nWHEATLEY, E. (Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 9 Bast UvarpooL Ohio\nFOR SECOND VICE PRESIDENT\n(Vote tor Ono)\nCARTWRIGHT, ALFRED R. (Tumor)\nLocal Union No. 10 East UvarpooL Ohio\nGARNER, WILLARD (Handler)\nLocal Union No. 10 East LivorpooL Ohio\nHULL. FRANK (Decorating Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 124 East UvarpooL Ohio\nWEST. HAROLD (Liner)\nLocal Union No. 124 East LivorpooL Ohio\nFOR THIRD VICE PRESIDENT\n(Vote for Ono)\nARMSTRONG, CLAIR (Docorating Elnman)\nLocal Union No. 124 East LivorpooL Ohio\nBOSSEN, WILLIAM F. (Tumor)\nLocal Union No. 10 .East UvarpooL Ohio\nSLAVEN, JAMES (Linar)\nLocal Union No. 124 East LivorpooL Ohio\nFOR FOURTH VICE PRESIDENT\n(Vote for Ono)\nPHILLIPS, VERNE D. (Sanitary Caster)\nLocal Union No. 50.. Camden, N. J.\nZIMMER. CHARLES (Sanitary Caster)\nLocal Union No. 45 Trenton, N. J.\nFOR FIFTH VICE PRESIDENT\n(Vote for One)\nDEVLIN, ARTHUR (Packer)\nLocal Union No. 184 Trenton. N. J.\nHIBBS, WILLIAM (Tumor)\nLocal Union No. 35 Trenton. N. J.\nPERDUNN, FRED (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 35 Trenton, N.\nFOR SIXTH VICE PRESIDENT\n(Veto for Ono)\nAPPLEGATE. FRANK M. (Kilnfiroman)\nLocal Union No. 51 _______ Sobring, Ohio\nBARKER, BEN. F. (Jiggonnan)\nLocal Union No. 12 East UvorpooL Ohio\nCAMPBELL WILLIAM J. (Jiggannan)\nLocal Union No. 103 .Erwin, Tenn.\nCOFFEY. JAMES (Kilnman) 1\nLocal Union No. 122 Cambridge, Ohio\nDALES. FRANK (Castor)\nLocal Union No. 4 East UvorpooL Ohio\nHAMILTON, B. R. (Doc) (Tumor)\nLocal Union No. 10 East UvorpooL Ohio\nSTARK. WILLIAM H. (Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 42 Salem, Ohio\nSNYDER, HENRY (Sanitary Caster)\nLocal Union No. 133 Now Castle, Pa.\nJIVIDEN. FLOYD (Kilnfiroman)\nLocal Union No. 130 East UvorpooL Ohio\nLLEWELLYN, JOSIAH (Dipper)\nLocal Union No. 201 Huntington Park, CaliL\nCOBB, CHAS. M. (Dish Jiggonnan)\nLocal Union No. 108 Bodford. Ohio\nSAMPLE BALLOT\nThe following is a replica of the official ballot for primary election of National Of\nficers and Delegates to the American Federation of Labor Convention, which in accord\nance with law, must be printed in each issue of the Potters Herald during the entire vot\ning period of the primary election.\nFOR SEVENTH VICE PRESIDENT\n(Vote for One)\nBEVAN, DAVID (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 99 Clarksburg, W. Va.\nBOSO, CHARLES B. (KQndrawer)\nLocal Union No. 17 East UvorpooL Ohio\nBOWMAN. WILLIAM C. (Sanitary Castor)\nLocal Union No, 133 Now Castle. Pa.\nBRATT, NORMAN H. (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 24 Wellsville, Ohio\nCURLEY, THOMAS A. (Handler)\nLocal Union No. 10---------------East UvorpooL Ohio\nDESMOND, T. J. (Dipper)\nLocal Union No. 70 Minerva, Ohio\nDIGMAN, GUY V. (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 12 East UvorpooL Ohio\nDORFF, JOHN A. (Art Ware Caster)\nLocal Union No. 178 Sobring, Ohio\nGUKISON, G. E_ Sr. (Tumor)\nLocal Union No. 10 _East UvorpooL Ohio\nHOUGH, JAMES LUTHER (Kilhman)\nLocal Unicm No. 9 .East UvorpooL Ohio\nMORROW, ROBERT (Warehouseman)\nLocal Union No. 42 Salem, Ohio\nSULLIVAN, JAMES (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 44 Sebring, Ohio\nSULLIVAN, O. (Pat) (Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 201 Huntington Park, CaliL\nWILLARD, WILBERT (Warehousemen)\nLocal Union No. 86 East Liverpool Ohio\nFOR EIGHTH VICE PRESIDENT\n(Vote for One)\nBRUNT. GEORGE (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 4 East UvorpooL Ohio\nCHADWICK. JOSHUA (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 12 East Liverpool Ohio\nDANIEL, WALTER G. (Decorating Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 124 East LivorpooL Ohio\nHALL LUTHER (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 12 East UvorpooL Ohio\nHAMILTON. JOHN W. (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 44 Sobring, Ohio\nLAWJON, SAMUEL (Tumor)\nLocal Unicm No. 24 Wellsville, Ohio\nUSK, FLOYD (Tally) (Handler)\nLocal Union No. 98 Grafton, W. Va.\nSCHAEFER. GEORGE (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 4 East LivorpooL Ohio\nSIMMONS, EARL (Trackman)\nLocal Union No. 98 Grafton. W. Va.\nWILSON. CLIFFORD (Kilnfireman)\nLocal Union No. 130 East LivorpooL Ohio\nFOR DELEGATES TO A. F. L.\nCONVENTION\n(Vote for One East of the Allegheny Mountains)\nBROWN. JOSEPH D. (Packer)\nLocal Union No. 35 Trenton, N. J.\nSIMPSON, JOHN (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 45 ____________Trenton. N. J.\n(Vote for Ono West of the Allegheny Mountains)\nBERRY, WILLIAM (Decorating Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 192 Sebring, Ohio\nBROWN, HAZEL (Liner)\nLocal Union No. 121 Sebring, Ohio\nBROADBENT, ROY (Kilnman)\nLocal Union No. 9 East UvorpooL Ohio\nCAMPBELL FRANK (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 122 Cambridge, Ohio\nDIGMAN, GUY V. (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 12 East UvorpooL Ohio\nEDWARDS, ABE (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 70 Minerva, Ohio\nGANT, PEARL EDWARD (Kilnfiroman)\nLocal Union No. 130 East UvorpooL Ohio\nEILLINGER, DAN (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 122 Cambridge, Ohio\nUSK, FLOYD (Tally) (Handler)\nLocal Union No. 98 Grafton, W. Va.\nMAMRACK, JOHN M. (Packer)\nLocal Union No. 51 Canonsburg, Pa.\nMANDLEY. FORM A. (Packer)\nLocal Union No. 70 Minerva, Ohio\nMcDEVITT, EDW. (Dipper)\nLocal Union No. 18 East Liverpool Ohio\nO'DOWD, JOHN W. (Handler)\nLocal Union No. 113 Los Angeles, CaliL\nPENNINGTON, FRED (Caster)\nLocal Union No. 113 Los Angeles, CaliL\nSELL THEODORE (Ted) (Jiggerman)\nLocal Union No. 12 .East UvorpooL Ohio\nVAN FOSSAN PAUL W. (Dipper)\n.Local Union No. 18 East UvorpooL Ohio\nWARD, JAMES (Warehouseman)\nLocal Union No. 86 East UvorpooL Ohio","height":"26205","width":"21042"}}
